			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Aon Study: Professional Liability Claims Up 9.7% a Year 
<br />

<br />
CHICAGO January 27 (BestWire) - As hospital and physician professional liability insurance rates continue to climb, a new study shows part of that increase is because claims are rising almost 10% a year.
<br />

<br />
Over the past three years, claims costs increased at a steady rate of 9.7%, with the same rate projected for 2004, according to the Hospital Professional Liability and Physician Liability Benchmark Study, produced by Aon's Risk Services. The study shows that trends in both the frequency--3%--and severity--6.5%--of claims are contributing to an overall 9.7% annual trend rate. 
<br />

<br />
It's beneficial for hospitals to use the benchmark for their funding considerations, the amount they're setting aside for 2004 to pay for these claims, said Greg Larcher, assistant director and actuary for Aon Actuarial and Analytics Practice. The marketplace is focused on premiums, but the results of this study show that claims activity is a significant contributor to the recent increases in market premiums, he said.
<br />

<br />
Hospital liability claims for 2004 are expected to average nearly $150,000 per claim, indicating that claim severity has nearly doubled since 1996, when the average was $79,000, the study said. Physician liability claims for the 2004 event year are expected to rise to an average $178,000, compared with $120,000 in 1996, the study said. 
<br />

<br />
"There has been little effect in this study due to tort reform," Larcher said. "It is too soon in most states for any reforms that have been passed in the recent years to show any effect."
<br />

<br />
One of the uses of the study is for hospitals to use the benchmark in planning their funding, as they plan how much income they will need to meet their costs in future years, Larcher said. The study takes the loss costs and breaks them out to a "per bed" benchmark both overall and for certain states, he said.
<br />

<br />
The study is more for the hospitals than for physicians, since most physicians are responsible for buying their own liability coverage, Larcher said. The exceptions are the larger physicians groups, some of which did provide information for the study, he said. Hospitals often contract with larger physician groups--in the range of 100 or more physicians--for some specific service such as emergency room service or anesthesiology, he said.
<br />

<br />
The majority of the cost for each claim continues to be the average allocated loss adjustment expense, compared with the indemnity per claim, the study showed. As of the 2002 claims year, average allocated expense was 81% of the total costs of claims, with 19% remaining for the indemnity cost, the study said. 
<br />

<br />
Average allocated loss adjustment expense refers to costs incurred in handling each claim and include legal fees paid and other costs for investigating and defending the claims, the study showed. Indemnity costs include payments and reserves for payments, the study said.
<br />

<br />
A Tillinghast study released in December shows total costs for the U.S. tort system rose 13.3% to $233 billion in 2002--a $27.4 billion increase over 2001--representing the largest dollar increase in U.S. history. The increase translates to an additional $809 paid by each U.S. citizen--$87 more than in 2001 and $797 more than in 1950. The study showed medical-malpractice costs totaled nearly $25 billion in 2002, or $85 per person, compared with $5 per person in 1975, outpacing all other tort costs (BestWire, Dec, 17, 2004).
<br />
(By John Hillman, associate editor, BestWeek: <a href="mailto:John.Hillman@ambest.com">John.Hillman@ambest.com</a>) BN-NJ-01-27-2004 1458 ET # </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
