				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The links you've posted are talking past the issue.
<br />

<br />
Of course insurance companies can remain profitable so long as they are able to hike their rates and/or deny coverage to certain specialties, that’s not the issue. Are you saying that these companies shouldn’t be able to make a profit?
<br />

<br />
The crisis is not spread evenly throughout the medical community. The level of crisis is only reached in a few specific specialties. A few of these are obstetrics, emergency medicine, trauma, etc.
<br />

<br />
These professions by no means make up a terribly large proportion of doctors. But, for obvious reasons, they are very important to have around.
<br />

<br />
I won’t defend the appearance of corruption perpetrated by the flow of money in this, and many other, industries. That doesn’t change the core issues though.
<br />

<br />
As to Florida already having addressed the issue, they may have. I’m no expert on Florida.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
