				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Ok then, what exactly are you saying there is a problem with? I am going on the assumption you are saying the problem is that malpractice insurance rates are rising so absurdly is because of the rise is med-mal suits. maybe we aren't on the same page here, since you never did define what you meant by "the problems with physicians and malpractice." You posted a quote of a study. You did not explain what specific problem you are talking about. If you are not talking about malpracitice insurances rates rising as a direct result of med-mal cases, then don't read the rest of my post. That is the premise I am basing the rest of this conversation on. 
<br />

<br />
Even still, I would like to have a more definitave answer to my question. What problem with physicians and malpractice are you speaking of? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
The main problem is twofold.
<br />
1. Malpractice insurance rates for high risk specialties are reaching a level where physicians are fleeing. They are fleeing by leaving for regions with lower premiums. They are fleeing by retiring early. They are fleeing by nature of less physicians entering the specialty in the first place. This is resulting in more patient loads for those who remain which results in more errors which results in higher premiums, etc.
<br />
2. General, lesser, increase in the expense of providing malpractice insurance and thus the decrease in profitability associated with that line of insurance is resulting in many of the larger insurers, and reinsurers, exiting the market. Some are exiting entirely while some are exiting in the most expensive regions. The decrease in the number of companies providing the coverage is creating an unstable marketplace and causing profitability to be crunched even further resulting in even more insurers leaving, or becoming insolvent.
<br />

<br />
Liability caps is one way of trying to address the problem. It may not be the best way. Nevertheless, something needs to be done quickly and it is better to try an unproven solution than to allow disagreement on a solution to gridlock the process and thus allow the problem to continue unchecked.
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> They are not taken out of context. If you would like the full transcript of the senate hearing, google it. It's public record. Go read it. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
