</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Florida doctors who care for women during pregnancy and childbirth now pay an average of $200,000 a year in premiums for $1 million in protection - the highest rates in the nation, reports the American College of Obstetrics and Gynecology. 
<br />

<br />
They pay almost as much in premiums each year as most doctors are ever likely to cost their insurance companies in a malpractice lawsuit. The average malpractice payment in 2001 was $219,122, against a national average of $219,461. That's according to the National Practitioners Databank, which tracks malpractice payments and doctor discipline cases. But obstetrics is widely considered the high-risk specialty by insurance companies and doctors groups because they get sued more than other doctors. The average payout against an obstetrician last year was $346,011. 
<br />

<br />
Other specialties, however, appear to pose higher risks of losses, Florida Today found. General practicioners accounted for the biggest share of total malpractice cases and payouts in 2002, followed by obstetricians and gynecologists. Dermatologists and pediatricians accounted for the highest average losses in malpractice cases: $506,667 and $472,200, respectively. Regional comparisons raise even more questions about the relative risks doctors pose to their insurors. 
<br />

<br />
Doctors working in Jacksonville pay $28,769 for a policy that costs doctors in Georgia $6,283 from the same company - even though Georgia's average malpractice payout in 2002 was 31 percent higher than Florida's. 
<br />

<br />
In the past, doctors could compensate for high insurance premiums by simply raising their rates for patients. That's what they did during similar malpractice crises in the mid-1970s and mid-1980s. Today, most of a physician's income comes from rates established Medicaid, HMOs and worker's compensation. That leaves doctors little flexibility. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
