<br />
<a href="http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2002/Jul-28-Sun-2002/news/19271188.html" target="_blank">http://www.reviewjournal.com/lvrj_home/2002/Jul-28-Sun-2002/news/19271188.html</a>
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Sunday, July 28, 2002
<br />
Copyright © Las Vegas Review-Journal 
<br />
THE MEDICAL MALPRACTICE INSURANCE CRISIS: Operation Special Session
<br />
Lawmakers face challenge of retaining doctors while allowing patients redress for mistakes 
<br />
By JOELLE BABULA 
<br />
REVIEW-JOURNAL 
<br />

<br />
The most critically injured patients in Southern Nevada could be denied life-saving trauma care, while newly pregnant women could be forced to travel out of state to find an obstetrician. 
<br />
Or, depending on the actions of lawmakers, brain-damaged patients and other severely injured victims of medical malpractice could face more obstacles in filing lawsuits and ultimately receive insufficient compensation. 
<br />
This week's special legislative session is expected to have far-reaching implications, as lawmakers attempt to strike a balance to ensure constituents have both access to medical care and redress for medical mistakes. 
<br />
The session was called Friday by Gov. Kenny Guinn to address Southern Nevada's looming medical crisis, which surfaced last fall when liability insurance companies began tripling and quadrupling medical malpractice premium rates. As rates skyrocketed, doctors began leaving the state or curtailing their services. 
<br />
Doctors say the only long-term solution is liability reform similar to California's, which includes a $250,000 cap on jury awards for pain and suffering. 
<br />
If lawmakers don't pass comprehensive tort reform, including caps on damages, then doctors say they will continue to leave the state or stop doing high-risk procedures, such as trauma care and obstetrics. 
<br />
Trial attorneys, however, say the cap won't lower premiums but will hurt victims of medical malpractice. 
<br />
If lawmakers pass liability reform similar to California's, victims of medical malpractice would get less money. This is especially true for babies and children, who, because they've never worked, are not eligible for recouping money for lost wages. 
<br />
Both the doctor and lawyer groups have launched advertising and public relations campaigns touting their side of the issue. 
<br />
Larry Matheis, executive director of the Nevada State Medical Association, estimates that more than 300 doctors are poised to leave Nevada if comprehensive tort reform is not passed this week. Most of those doctors are speciality surgeons and obstetricians. 
<br />
As many as 147 doctors already have left the state, retired early or are seriously considering shutting down their practices because they either can't find malpractice insurance or they can't afford the skyrocketing rates. 
<br />
"What's at stake here is whether patients will have access to the medical care they need at the time that they need it," Matheis said. "Even if they accomplish meaningful reform, we are still going to see deterioration in our system. Many of the physicians who have already started the process of relocating will continue." 
<br />
If there's no tort reform, Matheis said, "It wouldn't surprise me at all if something near 350 doctors leave the state or significantly change their practices so that they won't be available for most patients. If we lose that many physicians, then the recovery period for our health care system will take several years." 
<br />
Nevada lawmakers will have to determine next week what caused the medical insurance crisis for doctors and how to stem the continued exodus of physicians from the state while protecting a patient's right to seek redress in the courts. 
<br />
Causes debated 
<br />
Doctors and insurance company officials say frivolous lawsuits and large jury awards forced insurance companies to raise rates. 
<br />
Jury awards have increased dramatically since 1996, according to Clark County District Court records. 
<br />
In 1996, the total cost of jury awards was $225,000. In 1997, it was more than $500,000 and in 1998, the total increased to $3.5 million. In 1999 the amount was $10 million, followed by $5.5 million in 2000 and $21 million in 2001. 
<br />
Lawyers say the large jury awards are for catastrophically injured patients who need a lifetime of medical care. They say without the money, the state would end up picking up the tab for medical bills. 
<br />
The number of medical malpractice lawsuits filed in Clark County increased 439 percent from 1990 to 2001, according to a recent study by Clark County District Court. There were 33 medical malpractice cases filed in 1990 and 178 filed in 2001. 
<br />
According to the U.S. Census Bureau, during the same period, the population in Clark County increased by just over 100 percent. 
<br />
Trial lawyers offer a different perspective. They say that poor underwriting skills and an eagerness to insure even bad doctors to gain market share have forced companies to increase their rates. 
<br />
Although doctors say the medical malpractice insurance crisis had been brewing since early last year, its impact wasn't felt communitywide until the St. Paul Companies stopped offering liability coverage nationwide in December. 
<br />
The pullout of St. Paul, the largest insurer in the state, left the majority of Nevada doctors scrambling for new coverage. 
<br />
St. Paul pulled out of the market nationwide because of increasing jury awards and frivolous lawsuits, said its spokeswoman, Andrea Wood. 
<br />
Wood said the company paid out an average of $2 in losses for every $1 it collected from Nevada doctors between 1996 and 2001. 
<br />
St. Paul entered the Nevada liability market in 1996 when the company bought a doctor-owned insurance company, the Nevada Medical Legal Liability Company. Trial attorneys say St. Paul did everything it could to garner market share, including insuring bad doctors and keeping prices artificially low for several years. 
<br />
"They never raised premiums along the way to account for inflation, city growth, etcetera," said attorney Gerald Gillock. "Then the company takes a $90 million hit with Enron, as well as a stock market plummet followed by September 11 and they have to pull out worldwide. This allows for a feeding frenzy by other insurance companies." 
<br />
Wood said the company didn't immediately ask for rate increases when it began seeing losses in the mid-'90s. 
<br />
"We didn't accurately predict the losses and the severity of claims were much greater than we expected," she said. "When we began to realize the trend, we asked for rate increases everywhere, not just in Nevada, but that did not solve the problem for us." 
<br />
Wood said the stock market downturn had nothing to do with the company's solvency. 
<br />
"That assertion is ludicrous," she said. "We got out of the business because we were finding it difficult if not impossible to predict future exposure. We lost nearly $1.5 billion nationally over the last four years, and the stock market had nothing to do with that." 
<br />
Increased state oversight of insurance companies would not have prevented the pullout of St. Paul and the current medical malpractice insurance crisis, according to officials with the Nevada State Division of Insurance. 
<br />
"If this problem were unique to Nevada, the issue of more state oversight might be a legitimate one, but this is happening in many, many, many states," said Bruce Heffner, chief insurance assistant for the division. "Quite frankly, we have more state oversight than many other states." 
<br />
According to Heffner, St. Paul also had market share in Arkansas before the company left the market. The pullout in Arkansas, however, didn't create a crisis. Other companies were able to absorb the demand for insurance. 
<br />
"They felt it was viable to do business in Arkansas because of the legal climate," Heffner said. "The best way to solve the crisis in our state is to make the state more attractive to insurance companies." 
<br />
Arkansas does not have any type of cap on jury awards. 
<br />
Heffner said it would be too difficult and unfair to try to keep companies, such as St. Paul, from gaining market share. 
<br />
"Are you going to make them stop writing in a state so companies who are not so competitive can pick up more of the business?" he said. "We would have other problems if we started telling companies they could no longer compete in the state and then telling doctors they had to buy their insurance from someone more expensive." 
<br />
Other companies also are finding it increasingly difficult to do business in Nevada, said insurance company lobbyist and attorney Jim Wadhams. 
<br />
"The Nevada marketplace for medical malpractice is no longer predictable," Wadhams said. "There are four or five companies that still insure doctors all over the state, but they don't want to write anybody new. They have some dandy little safe doctors, and they can't afford to take on any more risk." 
<br />
Wadhams said the insurance problems are more severe in Las Vegas than in other cities because the state has so few doctors. 
<br />
"A very few number of bad apples will dramatically spoil the barrel because we have so few," Wadhams said. "Just a couple of big settlements, for any reason and suddenly that's a lot of money dumped on a very small base." 
<br />
There are about 4,200 active, licensed doctors in the state of Nevada, including 2,720 in Clark County. 
<br />
Nevada has one of the lowest rates of doctors to population base in the country, according to a 2000 report by the American Medical Association. The state is ranked 47th, with 196 doctors per 100,000 people. Massachusetts ranks No. 1, with 446 doctors per 100,000 people. 
<br />
Consequences unknown 
<br />
As lawmakers contemplate damage caps next week, they will have to decide what, if any, amount will help ensure patient access to health care and simultaneously not harm victims of medical malpractice. 
<br />
Both insurance companies and doctors want to see lawmakers pass some sort of a cap on jury awards for pain and suffering. California's $250,000 cap is ideal, they say, but higher caps may be entertained as well. 
<br />
A cap would not limit the amount of money an injured patient could collect for medical expenses and lost wages. It would, however, punish the most vulnerable patients, namely children, because they can't collect money for lost wages, said attorney Gillock, who has been active in the reform debate. 
<br />
Gillock said one of his clients, Jason Phillips, nearly lost his 3-year-old daughter because of a mistreated ear infection that turned out to be spinal meningitis. 
<br />
Brittany Phillips, now 12, was a healthy, precocious 3-year-old with a better vocabulary than her 5-year-old brother. Now, after suffering several strokes because of what Gillock describes as a misdiagnosis along with delayed care, Brittany is severely brain damaged and suffers physical disabilities. 
<br />
She will never have more than the mental capacity of a 5-year-old, her father said. 
<br />
"She'll never be able to get a job or get married. She can't brush her teeth, comb her hair and needs assistance going to the bathroom." 
<br />
"I have dreams about her waking me up and asking me, `What happened daddy?' in that voice she used to have," her father said. "But what we have is what we're going to have for the rest of her life. I know it could be worse. At least she's alive." 
<br />
Phillips settled the Las Vegas case out of court, and the confidential settlement amount is enough to handle Brittany's medical bills. But he believes that victims should be able to get more than $250,000 for pain and suffering if they go to court. 
<br />
If Brittany's case had gone to court, as a child she would have been ineligible for economic damages for lost wages. 
<br />
"This kind of case would have totally been obliterated by the cap," he said. "This is one of those instances where a cap would be a severe injustice." 
<br />
Without a cap or other liability reforms, however, Nevadans could wind up traveling out of state for medical care. 
<br />
More than half of the 90 obstetricians that deliver babies in Clark County are not taking any newly pregnant patients, including longtime patients who become pregnant, said Dr. John Nowins, president of the Clark County OB/GYN Society. 
<br />
The doctors are waiting to see what happens in the Legislature before they decide to take new patients or leave the state altogether. 
<br />
The future of Southern Nevada's only trauma center also is at risk. 
<br />
The center closed for 10 days earlier this month after surgeons quit working at the facility because of liability issues. The facility at University Medical Center reopened after the doctors came back to work temporarily, acting in good faith, they said, that lawmakers would pass significant tort reform. 
<br />
The trauma center takes care of victims of car accidents, gunshot and stab wounds and other critically injured patients 24 hours a day, seven days a week. Without the center, patients will have to be transported to the nearest emergency room, where doctors usually aren't trained to perform surgeries. 
<br />
"We have a lot of general surgeons on staff who say, `Look, I haven't done trauma in more than 10 years, and I don't even have my advanced trauma life certificate anymore. Please don't call me in for trauma,' " said Dr. Paul Fischer, director of the emergency department at Sunrise Hospital and Medical Center. "They make a good point. Both the doctors and the patients are at risk." 
<br />
Fischer also said he's concerned about what will happen to pregnant women and babies if too many obstetricians leave the state or limit their services. 
<br />
"If no one is available, those women will start coming to emergency rooms, and that will not be good," Fischer said. "Although we are trained to perform emergency obstetric procedures, we do one maybe every 10 years. You just don't want to find yourself with a doctor that does the procedure that you need once every 10 years. There's definitely potential for a worse outcome."
<br />
 </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.iii.org/media/hottopics/insurance/medicalmal/" target="_blank">http://www.iii.org/media/hottopics/insurance/medicalmal/</a>
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Medical Malpractice
<br />
 	THE TOPIC
<br />
 
<br />
SEPTEMBER 2003
<br />
 
<br />
Medical malpractice insurance covers doctors and other professionals in the medical field for liability claims arising from their treatment of patients. 
<br />

<br />
The cost of medical malpractice insurance has been rising. The hard market began in 2000, after almost a decade of essentially flat prices. Rate increases have been precipitated in part by the growing size of claims, more frequent claims in some urban areas and soaring defense costs. Losses are growing at a time when investment income, the cushion against losses, is declining, thus widening the gap between revenues (premiums) and claims. In addition reinsurance, insurance for insurers, has become much more expensive, pushing up insurers' costs. Among the other factors driving up prices is a reduced supply of available coverage as insurers exit the medical malpractice business because of the difficulty of making a profit. 
<br />

<br />
California, which has had a $250,000 cap on noneconomic damages since 1975, is one of the handful of states where rates are stable because losses are more predictable. 
<br />
 	
<br />
 	KEY FACTS
<br />
 
<br />
&amp;#61607;	The median (midpoint) of medical malpractice jury awards was $1 million in 2001, a 43 percent jump from $700,000 in 1999. However, the largest award at $131,700,000 was more than twice the previous year’s largest award and the largest in at least six years. Award ranges have also been trending upward for at least the last six years.
<br />
&amp;#61607;	The medical malpractice combined ratio, a measure of profitability, reached 153.3 in 2001, compared with 115.7 for all lines combined. This deterioration occurred in spite of a rise in premiums of 8.7 percent that year. Estimates show that in 2002 the combined ratio continued to worsen, reaching 165.
<br />
&amp;#61607;	Society must balance a citizen's right to sue as a result of errors in medical treatment against the cost of lawsuits and ensuring continued access to medical practitioners. 
<br />

<br />
 	
<br />
 	CURRENT DEVELOPMENTS
<br />
 
<br />
Studies: A June 2003 General Accounting Office survey, “Medical Malpractice Insurance: Multiple Factors Have Contributed to Increased Premium Rates,” confirms the need for tort reform in the area of medical liability. The survey concluded that high payments on legal claims in some states was the primary factor causing medical malpractice insurance rates to rise. The survey focused on malpractice insurance rates in seven states — California, Florida, Minnesota, Mississippi, Nevada, Pennsylvania, and Texas — and found that rate increases varied greatly from state to state and from one medical specialty to another. While general surgeons in Florida paid 75 percent more for insurance in 2002, compared with 1999, rates for Minnesota doctors increased by only 2 percent during the same period. Only 12 states in the United States, do not limit jury awards for pain and suffering in medical malpractice cases.
<br />

<br />
Meanwhile, a June 2003 report by Weiss Ratings found that capping medical malpractice noneconomic damages does not appreciably affect the pricing of medical malpractice insurance. The Physician Insurance Association of America called the study fatally flawed for focusing on median premiums rather than the spiraling rise in total claim payments caused by a greater proportion of large payments. It also noted that median premiums should be weighted by market share. 
<br />

<br />
Earlier this year the Joint Economic Committee of the U.S. Congress released a study entitled “Liability for Medical Malpractice: Issues and Evidence,” that noted that the past several years have witnessed a considerable increase in the cost and impact of medical malpractice litigation. The result of this has been higher malpractice insurance premiums for health care providers, which in turn has led to higher costs for the health care system as well as reduced access to medical services. In 2001, medical malpractice insurance topped $21 billion, double the amount ten years earlier. Of the 2001 amount, $7.2 billion was purchased through traditional means and the rest through alternative markets. 
<br />

<br />
The study concluded that reforming the medical liability system could produce significant benefits such as realizing important savings on health care spending; reducing unnecessary tests and treatments motivated out of fear of litigation; encouraging systematic reform efforts to identify and reduce medical errors; halting the exodus of doctors from high-litigation states and specialties; improving access to health care, particularly benefiting women, low-income individuals and rural residents; and increasing the number of Americans with health insurance by as many as 3.9 million people. The study also found that reforming the current lawsuit-based tort system could save the federal government in the neighborhood of $67 billion over the next 10 years.
<br />

<br />
Federal Legislation: Hopes for a federal solution to the medical malpractice insurance crisis were dashed in July when Senate Democrats killed a House medical malpractice liability reform bill that would have limited noneconomic damage awards in medical malpractice lawsuits to $250,000, restrict attorneys’ fees using a sliding scale (from 40 percent of the first $50,000 to 15 percent for awards over $600,000), impose a statute of limitations on the filing of such cases (three years from the date of the injury and one year from discovery), and assign proportional liability for the damage according to responsibility. On the heels of this defeat Senator Michael Enzi of Wyoming said he would introduce a proposal to establish special state medical courts with expert judges to hear cases and decide awards. 
<br />

<br />
Availability: In March 2003 the American Medical Association increased the number of states where medical liability has reached crisis proportions from 12 to 18. The new states where conditions are critical are Arkansas, Connecticut, Illinois, Kentucky, Missouri and North Carolina. The states that were already on the list are Florida, Georgia, Mississippi, Nevada, New Jersey, New York, Ohio, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Texas, Washington and West Virginia. 
<br />

<br />
With the cost of claims soaring, medical malpractice insurers continue to leave the market and many in the medical community are experiencing difficulties finding affordable insurance. The latest withdrawal from the market is that of Princeton Insurance Co., New Jersey’s largest medical malpractice insurer, to stop writing new policies in the state in August as a result of a failure to get sufficient reinsurance. 
<br />

<br />
In New York, Insurance Commissioner Gregory Serio recently approved an average 8.5 percent increase in the rates the state’s insurers charge for medical malpractice insurance. New York doctors expressed concern that the relatively small average rate increase approved by the state’s regulators would result in a lack of support for legislation proposed to reform the state’s malpractice laws. New York doctors already pay some of the highest malpractice premiums in the U.S.
<br />

<br />
In Maryland, the state’s leading medical malpractice insurer, the Medical Mutual Liability Insurance Society of Maryland, which insures about 80 percent of the state’s doctors in private practice, filed a request for a rate increase of 28 percent. The state’s medical society, MedChi, is considering tort reform possibilities, including further limits on awards and on attorneys’ fees. Maryland has a cap of $620,000 on noneconomic damages awards and does not permit punitive damages in medical malpractice cases.
<br />

<br />
Another example of a medical malpractice insurer struggling to survive is Reciprocal of America, which the Virginia insurance department placed in receivership on January 29, 2003. Reciprocal is a malpractice underwriter that provides liability insurance to more than 150 hospitals in Virginia and is licensed to do business in 40 states and the District of Columbia. In a domino effect, Tennessee regulators placed three more medical malpractice underwriters, all reinsured by the Virginia company, under administrative supervision. 
<br />

<br />
Some states that have not managed to pass meaningful tort reform have been forced to address the problem through other temporary measures. For example, on April 24 Mississippi Gov. Ronnie Musgrove signed into law a bill creating an insurance pool for doctors and hospitals in the state that are having trouble finding coverage in the private market. The pool was given $500,000 in startup costs but will be self-supporting. The program will expire in 2005. 
<br />

<br />
State Reform Proposals: Tort reform proposals that address the current medical malpractice liability crisis are making their way through the legislatures of a number of states, with varying degrees of success. While proposals differ from state to state, almost all contain caps on noneconomic damages. Two large states that have recently passed reform legislation are Florida and Texas. In Florida, where rates are among the highest in the country and where twice as many doctors get sued as in other states, one in six, compared with one in 12 nationwide, Governor Jeb Bush pushed through a bill to reduce medical malpractice insurance costs. The law limits a doctor's liability for noneconomic damages in most cases to $500,000 and a medical facility's liability to $750,000 in most cases. Multiple victims will be able to receive more with multiple lawsuits, but no group of victims could win more than $2.5 million. Economic damages will not be capped. In May 2003 iBXe Group, a Deerfield Beach, Florida-based health care consulting firm, released a study that found that if a $250,000 cap on pain and suffering damages in medical malpractice cases were in effect, it would have cut 25 percent of the $1.2 billion in malpractice settlements and awards paid in Florida from 1999 through 2002. 
<br />

<br />
In Texas, Governor Rick Perry signed a medical malpractice bill that caps noneconomic damages cases at $250,000 per defendant, for a possible total of $750,000. The legislation will face a voter referendum in September to make the change part of the state constitution, a step needed to protect the legislation from being annulled by a court decision.
<br />

<br />
Following Missouri Gov. Bob Holden’s veto of a tort reform bill that contained a number of provisions unrelated to medical malpractice, the Missouri State Medical Association now says it would support legislation dealing solely with medical malpractice concerns. 
<br />

<br />
In a shift of position, New Jersey, Insurance Commissioner Holly Bakke says that she favors dropping, for the time being, any attempt to cap noneconomic damages in medical malpractice cases and supports subsidies to help doctors pay for their insurance. She also suggests that reimbursement for doctors needs attention, noting that while doctors used to be able to pass their insurance costs along to patients in the past, they can no longer do so because most are under contracts with HMOs. And she wants insurers to look more carefully at the fact that a small percentage of doctors are responsible for a disproportionate number of claims and that doctors in particularly risky specialties, e.g. obstetrics and neurosurgery, are penalized for taking on the risks. She noted that the medical malpractice insurance crisis has been slightly alleviated by the increasing number of claims-made policies now available in the state. An earlier proposal to set a $300,000 limit on insurers’ liability for noneconomic damages in malpractice cases, with damage awards over $300,000 being paid from a fund created through a surcharge on doctors, lawyers and employers is dead.
<br />

<br />
Pennsylvania, one of the states most seriously affected by the medical malpractice liability insurance crisis, continues to grapple with the problem. The Pennsylvania Department of Insurance released a new study showing that medical malpractice insurers lost $18 million in their operations in the state last year. The analysis shows that even after accounting for reserves, malpractice insurance underwriters in Pennsylvania incurred losses in 2002 for the fourth consecutive year. The state authorities said that the malpractice underwriters earned $46.4 million in investment income last year while paying out $345.9 million in claims, $136.9 million in legal costs and $81.1 million for taxes and other operating expenses. In response, Governor Ed Rendell has proposed state subsidies of $200 million to help doctors pay for insurance over the next three years. Doctors in the state buy the first $500,000 of coverage from private insurers and the second $500,000 from the state’s catastrophic insurance MCARE Fund. 
<br />

<br />
In March 2003 West Virginia Governor Bob Wise signed into law a bill that caps medical malpractice pain and suffering awards at $250,000, except in cases of wrongful death or bodily impairment, when the cap is $500,000. Another provision in the bill calls for a doctor-owned and managed physicians' mutual insurance company to be up and running no later than July 1, 2004. 
<br />

<br />
Other states where medical malpractice reform is on the legislative agenda are Nevada and Mississippi. In May 2003 Nevada Gov. Kenny Guinn signed into law a bill that prohibits medical malpractice insurers from using any financial loss sustained through investments as justification for increasing premiums paid by doctors. The law also includes a provision that prohibits medical malpractice insurers from basing rates for obstetricians on the number of babies they deliver in a year. In July 2002 the state passed a bill limiting noneconomic damages to $325,000, adopting new joint-and-several liability standards for economic damages, limiting physician liability in government and nonprofit trauma facilities to $50,000, and other provisions. In October 2002 Mississippi passed a law capping noneconomic damages at $500,000, requiring cases to be filed only in the county where the cause of action occurred, shortening the statute of limitations for suing nursing homes from three to two years, and other provisions.
<br />

<br />
High Risk Specialties: Obstetricians and gynecologists (OB GYNs) are among specialists who have been most seriously affected by rate increases because they are among the most vulnerable to lawsuits. Medical Liability Monitor newsletter reports that OB GYNs’ medical malpractice insurance premiums rose by an average 9.2 percent in 2001 and are expected to rise by 19.3 percent in 2002.
<br />

<br />
A recent survey from the Council of State Neurosurgical Societies showed that in more than half the states the threat of lawsuits has risen and as many as 43 percent of neurosurgeons, a high-risk group, have either restricted their practices or are considering taking other steps to avoid the high cost of insurance.
<br />

<br />
Jury Awards and Settlements: There are court verdicts in only a small portion of medical malpractice cases and the majority of claims are settled in favor of defendants. However, settlement amounts are substantially influenced by the size of recent awards. And defense costs, which are generally paid by insurers, can be high even when the defendant wins. In 2001, defense costs in medical malpractice cases made up 30 percent of the total loss costs, according to A.M. Best.
<br />

<br />
Evidence of soaring costs can be found in recent Jury Verdict Research data that show that the median medical malpractice jury award in 2001 (the latest year for which complete data are available) was $1 million, a 43 percent increase over the 1999 figure of $700,000. However, the largest award at $131,700,000 was more than twice the previous year’s largest award and the largest in at least six years. Mean awards and award ranges have been trending upward for at least the last six years as well. Medical negligence in childbirth resulted in the highest median award. 
<br />

<br />
About 54 percent of all medical malpractice awards, based on Jury Verdict Research data, now are over $1 million, compared with 43 percent during the period 1998-1999. However, medical malpractice awards are subject to considerable volatility and very large awards are often reduced on appeal. These statistics are drawn from the original awards. Jury Verdict Research data also show that while death was the most frequent claim, brain injury was the second most frequent and by far the most costly, with the median award at $4.5 million and the probable range of awards from $1.4 million to $11.2 million.
<br />

<br />
Impact of Managed Care: According to a 2001 study of the medical malpractice insurance business by Conning Research &amp; Consulting, Inc., managed care has changed the focus of medical malpractice from "committed medical acts to omitted ones, largely as a result of the increased rationing of medical services." The Conning study also points out that heightened attention to patient safety and publicity surrounding the incidence of hospital errors is likely to push up medical practice claims. 
<br />

<br />
Financial Results: The insurance market for business insurance, including medical malpractice, tends to be cyclical. The current hard market for medical malpractice has been exacerbated by the shortage of reinsurance, insurance for insurers, which is pushing up insurers' costs, and also by soaring awards in medical malpractice cases. Although the severity of the problems differ from one state to another and even within states, most are seeing higher jury awards and consequently higher settlements because award amounts influence demands and settlement negotiations. The drop in investment income generated by the stock and bond markets widens the gap between premium income and claims payouts. 
<br />

<br />
The medical malpractice combined ratio, a measure of profitability, reached 153.3 in 2001, compared with 115.7 for all lines combined. This means that insurers on average have been paying out $1.53 for every dollar they collected in premiums. This deterioration occurred in spite of a rise in premiums of 8.7 percent that year. Estimates show that in 2002 the combined ratio continued to worsen, reaching 165. In most of the 1990s, when the bull market and higher interest rates generated higher earnings on securities, investment income helped offset underwriting losses. In addition, insurers were keeping rates artificially low by using reserves accumulated in earlier years, but reserves are now depleted. The combined ratio hit the 160 percent mark for several years at the height of the last medical malpractice crisis in the mid-1980s. Several states, following California’s lead, enacted substantial tort reforms as a result of that crisis (See Background). 
<br />

<br />
Also contributing to the problem of the ever-increasing size of claims are health care costs. In the 1990s, managed care helped keep costs low but most of the available savings have now been realized. Health care costs have been rising for several years and a jump of as much as 15 percent is forecast for 2003. A small portion of the rise is attributable to medical malpractice insurance rate increases. Medical malpractice premiums contribute about 1 percent to the overall cost of health care. During the last crisis, doctors could pass on their higher insurance costs to patients but now that is more difficult because in many cases prices are controlled by contracts negotiated with health maintenance organizations. 
<br />
 	
<br />
 	BACKGROUND
<br />
 
<br />
Brief History: The medical malpractice insurance system experienced a period of crisis in the early 1970s, when several private insurers left the market because of rising claims and inadequate rates. The exodus of capacity resulted in an availability crisis. Over the next fifteen years, various attempts were made to ease the explosion in claims costs — tort reform, increased diagnostic testing, improved peer review, and increased communication between doctors and patients. These efforts appear to have had a positive impact. The number of claims dropped. However, the size of claims — the dollar amount — has continued to grow, although initially not at the fast pace reported earlier in the decade.
<br />

<br />
Aggressive campaigns to reform state laws governing medical liability lawsuits began in the 1970s. Every state except West Virginia passed reforms. New Hampshire's entire reform act was subsequently struck down as unconstitutional by its Supreme Court, but Indiana's, which was the most comprehensive in the nation when it went into effect in 1975, has been found constitutional in all challenges and has helped to keep physicians' premiums down in that state. California's Medical Injury Compensation Reform Act (MICRA), also enacted in 1975, which caps noneconomic damages and modifies the collateral source rule, is also considered a model law, see below.
<br />

<br />
Responding to the problem of availability, physicians formed doctor-owned malpractice insurance companies to provide coverage. These companies now write about half of all the medical malpractice insurance in the nation. Since these new companies had not experienced any losses, they could initially charge much lower rates. Later they suffered the fate of their private insurer predecessors, having to pay claims of increasing frequency and size as prior malpractice incidents of those they insured came to light. This, in turn, necessitated charging higher insurance rates.
<br />

<br />
Reasons for the increased incidence of malpractice claims are not entirely clear, but several contributing factors have been suggested. In addition to the fact that people became more litigious than in the past, the crisis of the 1970s, which was extensively reported by the media, may have made people more aware of physicians' vulnerability to malpractice suits. Other factors were the loss of an intimate relationship between families and their doctors and the use of medical experts to testify in malpractice cases. Physicians have also accused lawyers of being excessively eager to bring malpractice suits because of the high fees the lawyers can collect when their clients win. 
<br />

<br />
More recently, there has been a rise in public distrust of the medical profession and publicity about the number of medical errors which has led the public to believe standards are declining when in fact the reverse is true. In addition, changes in the judicial environment are increasing costs. It is easier to litigate, to find counsel and build a case using information on the Internet, for example. Some industry observers say that juries have become desensitized to large numbers. While awards do get reduced, the results of appeals are not publicized, which leads to higher claim demands and settlements. Others cite a growing resentment to large for-profit health care firms, the caliber and strength of the plaintiffs' bar and a greater willingness on the part of physicians to testify against another physician. 
<br />

<br />
Prevalence of Medical Malpractice: A study (generally known as the Harvard study) commissioned by New York State in 1986, and released in 1990, showed that actual malpractice is relatively rare. Of the New York hospital cases examined, the incidence of adverse events, or injuries resulting from medical "interventions" or treatment, was 3.7 percent. The percentage of adverse events due to what the physician team characterized as "negligence" (not necessarily a legal definition) was 1 percent. However, only one in eight who suffered from an adverse event due to negligence filed a medical malpractice claim, and only one in 15 received compensation. Most adverse events resulted in only minimal and transient disability and most of the patients' medical care expenses were paid for by health insurance. This helps to explain why only a small percentage of patients who are injured as a result of negligence file medical malpractice claims. However, a significant portion (22 percent) of patients who did not file medical malpractice claims suffered moderate or greater incapacity. In a second phase of the study, researchers confirmed that some of the tort claims filed provided little or no evidence of medical malpractice or even an adverse event, suggesting that the tort system is "very error-prone," at least in its initial stages.
<br />

<br />
Effects of Tort Reform: Between February 1986 and May 1987 the General Accounting Office issued five reports on medical malpractice. The third, published in December 1986, "Medical Malpractice: Six State Case Studies Show Claims and Insurance Costs Still Rise Despite Reforms," singled out the reforms enacted in California in 1975 as among the most effective in moderating increases in the cost of malpractice insurance and the size of awards. 
<br />

<br />
California’s reforms have helped stabilize the medical malpractice environment in that state, making the coverage more affordable than in many other urban areas. MICRA has seven major elements: a collateral source rule which requires that juries be told when plaintiffs have other sources of compensation for their injuries, a cap of $250,000 on noneconomic awards such as compensation for pain and suffering, and periodic payments rather a lump sum for awards of more than $50,000. It also requires lawsuits generally to be filed within three years of the injury, includes a specific scale for attorney’s fees, requires that plaintiffs' attorneys give 90 days advance notice to the defendant of their intention to file a lawsuit, and stipulates that contracts for medical services may include provisions for binding arbitration. 
<br />
 	
<br />
 	© Insurance Information Institute, Inc. - ALL RIGHTS RESERVED </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://csms.org/content/showpage.asp?page=lu3" target="_blank">http://csms.org/content/showpage.asp?page=lu3</a>
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Response to PRI Recommendations
<br />
CSMS acknowledges and appreciates that the committee has incorporated some of our recommendations. We are concerned, however, that the report has no actuarial basis to prove the recommendations would have a significant impact on premiums. Further, we are concerned the proposed solution does not acknowledge the systemic problems. By not establishing standards, including limits for non-economic damages, the root cause goes unaddressed. Without a standard, there is no predictability; without predictability, insurance does not work.
<br />
We firmly believe the system is broken and the Committee’s recommendations will not fix it. We respectfully submit the following comments on PRI’s recommendations.
<br />
PRI Recommendations
<br />
1. Medical Liability Insurance Premium Assistance Fund The CSMS has grave concerns over whether this proposal will adequately address the staggering increases in medical malpractice premiums. We question the underlying data used to establish the fund, and caution that there are approximately 7,000 practicing physicians in Connecticut. This change alone drops the fund balance to approximately $2m. Taking Obs, one of the numerous specialties suffering from an unstable medical malpractice market, their average premium increase from 03 to 04 is $25,000. There are 450 practicing Obs in CT, so relief for this single specialty would be about $11m. Neurologists, radiologists, all primary care physicians (internal medicine, family practice, etc.) are finding it difficult at best and impossible at worst to find affordable coverage.
<br />
This proposal fails to acknowledge several key facts: 1.) Premium increases are not isolated to a few physicians in a few specialties, 2) The number of physicians assumed is inaccurate, and 3.) It assumes if a physician is sued, and a judgment is made against the physician, that physician is "a bad doctor." In fact, risky treatment or a difficult condition often determines the outcome and, thus, the filing of a claim for compensation.
<br />
CSMS respectfully asks that this proposal be reviewed by actuaries to ensure that it in deed will accomplish what you intend it to accomplish.
<br />
2. Offer of Judgment: CSMS sees the changes as an improvement over current practice, but would encourage the committee to make further modifications - consistent with IAC and CBIA recommendations - to ensure changes in the amount of the claim after the original offer of judgment would recalculate at the time of such change.
<br />
3. Good Faith Certificate: CSMS sees this recommendation as an improvement over current practice, but cautions that, without an actuarial review, the premium savings needed to re-energize the failing medical malpractice insurance industry will not be achieved.
<br />
4. Pre-suit Mediation: Currently, either party can request mediation. This recommendation makes it mandatory if either party makes a request. Unfortunately, the pre-suit mediation process is not focused on determining whether the practitioner has met the appropriate standard of care for the service, but instead is focused on the outcome and on compensation awards. CSMS believes that determining liability through mandated Pre-Trial Screening Panels will have a more direct and profound impact on the crisis than updating the current process for pre-suit mediation.
<br />
5. Attorney’s Fees: CSMS views this recommendation as positive for patients where a jury has determined compensation, providing the lion’s share of awards to plaintiffs.
<br />
6. Stakeholder Task Force: Given the severity of the crisis for physicians in CT, further study without immediate significant and actuarially sound solutions will further erode the access to care situation. CSMS is opposed to delaying action in lieu of more study.
<br />
7. Insurance Regulation: CSMS would support further insurance oversight if such oversight would not jeopardize a competitive marketplace and would provide physicians with alternatives for coverage. We are concerned that the recommendation for the commissioner to determine annually the type of regulation for medical malpractice carriers would create a huge disincentive for companies to do business in CT, and would create further erosion in the number of carriers doing business in CT or the services and treatment they would be willing to insure.
<br />
8. Physician Discipline: CSMS continues to maintain a commitment to improving patient safety in CT. CSMS supports CME. CSMS supports clarifying DPH protocol for physician investigations. However, we have serious concerns over several elements of these recommendations. We caution the committee that an unworkable administrative system would develop. This system would be too cumbersome to accomplish the goal of evaluating and addressing issues of standard of care.
<br />
What is missing?
<br />
CSMS strongly urges the Committee incorporate several other recommendations into this report, based on our findings that they can contribute to stabilizing the medical liability environment.
<br />
1. Actuarial analysis of the recommendations - CSMS believes that the legislature is committed to making changes that will, indeed, reduce premium costs for medical liability insurance. To ensure that this is the case, a third party analysis is warranted.
<br />
2. Periodic Payments - CSMS supports mandating periodic payments for damage awards in excess of $200,000. Plaintiffs should not be able to require lump sum payments.
<br />
3. Relief for practitioners volunteering their services - The CSMS supports the expansion of the Good Samaritan law to include health care services provided for free within a community clinic.
<br />
4. Pre-Trial mechanism - CSMS supports amending Connecticut law to require the use of a pre-trial screening panel, currently a voluntary process. States such as Maine, Montana and New Mexico have experienced positive results in the adjudication of malpractice cases through the establishment of pre-trial screening panels. These panels help to separate cases of negligence from cases of bad outcome. In addition, both plaintiffs and defendants benefit from a more speedy facilitation of claims.
<br />
5. Whistleblower Protection - CSMS supports the creation of review processes structured to encourage and protect physicians who come forward to report potential problems concerning practitioners, and who participate in the necessary committees, processes and structures to fairly assess and address potential problem practitioners. Extending whistleblower protection for physicians who report to or participate in peer review activities outside of the Department of Public Health (DPH) reporting system would encourage reporting and strengthen physician participation in peer review. Currently only those reporting directly to DPH enjoy whistleblower protection.
<br />
6. Limitations on non-economic damages - States with limits on non-economic damages have consistently demonstrated lower premium rates and smaller rate increases than those states without limits. Providing predictability on the amounts of these awards is critical to stabilizing rates. CSMS supports a limit on non-economic damages without loopholes, interpreted by actuaries to provide the relief necessary to decrease anticipated increases in premiums for 2004 and beyond. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.findarticles.com/cf_dls/m0CYD/6_38/99376486/p1/article.jhtml" target="_blank">http://www.findarticles.com/cf_dls/m0CYD/6_38/99376486/p1/article.jhtml</a>
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Obstetrics being dropped due to malpractice costs: in one survey, 56% ponder relocating. (Results of Two Surveys).
<br />
OB/GYN News, March 15, 2003, by Joyce Frieden
<br />

<br />
The malpractice crisis is causing many ob.gyns. to drop obstetrics from their practices, according to two recent surveys.
<br />
The most recent numbers come from Merritt, Hawkins, &amp; Associates, an Irving, Tex.-based physician-recruiting firm. Merritt Hawkins sent surveys to 4,000 ob.gyns. in 12 states that have been identified by the American Medical Association as being in a "malpractice crisis" due to sharply rising premiums: West Virginia, Ohio, Pennsylvania, Florida, Georgia, Mississippi, Nevada, New Jersey, New York, Oregon, Texas, and Washington.
<br />
Of the 268 physicians who responded, 95% said they were experiencing rising malpractice premiums, and 56% said the increases were forcing them to consider relocating to another state. Of those considering relocating, 59% were already actively taking steps to do so by researching practice opportunities, talking to potential employers, or taking other measures.
<br />
The survey also found that 39% of respondents were discontinuing their obstetrics practices.
<br />
These data are in agreement with what the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists found in its own survey of 28,000 members nationwide over the summer according to ACOG officials. That survey which included more than 6,500 responses from members in 11 "crisis" states, also asked ob.gyns. what measures they had taken as a result of the malpractice crisis. In those 11 states, 984 of the 6,560 respondents indicated they had stopped practicing obstetrics due to medical liability insurance availability and affordability issues. The highest percentage was in Nevada, where nearly 20% had stopped doing obstetrics; the lowest was Texas, at 10%.
<br />
ACOG officials noted that the Merritt Hawkins survey showed that ob.gyns. are performing an average of 186 deliveries per year. That number was higher than a 1999 AGOG survey, which found that ob.gyns. were averaging 162 deliveries per year. If ACOG's numbers are used, it could mean that as many as 159,408 pregnant women in the 11 crisis states will-annually be forced to find new physicians to provide their obstetric care. ACOG would like to see federal tort reform legislation passed that would include a cap on noneconomic damages, preferably in the S250,000 range, said Dr. Al Strunk, vice-president for fellowship activities at ACOG, in Washington.
<br />
Most ob.gyns. appear to be hoping that either the federal or state government will solve their problems; of those that have discontinued obstetrics, 83% said they would restart their obstetrics practices if tort reform were enacted and malpractice premiums became reasonable, according to the Merritt Hawkins survey.
<br />
Although many physicians agree that rising malpractice premiums are caused by an increase in malpractice suits and higher damage awards, that's not the case, according to the Association of Trial Lawyers of America (ATLA). According to the organization's Web site, investment losses by malpractice insurers, not bigger damage payouts, are what is driving premiums way up. The solution, the group says, is to fully disclose errors to patients right away and preemptively offer them compensation. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/09/15/focus11.html" target="_blank">http://www.bizjournals.com/columbus/stories/2003/09/15/focus11.html</a>
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Pa. doctors blame exodus on malpractice premiums
<br />
Tracy Carbasho
<br />
For Business First
<br />
Information released by the Pennsylvania Medical Society shows the state lost more than 1,000 physicians between 2001 and 2002, leaving behind colleagues who blame the exodus on the malpractice crisis. 
<br />
"People have to realize that you can't have a Cadillac health care system for free. It can't be an entitlement," said Dr. Bryan LaBuda, an obstetrician/gynecologist who practices at the Moraca Ob/Gyn Associates, which has offices in Sewickley, Wexford and Moon Township. 
<br />
"Having access to quality physicians will continue to be a problem as more good doctors leave or retire. It's also going to be a problem trying to get good physicians to come here because of the insurance premiums, the litigation environment and poor reimbursements," he said. 
<br />
LaBuda, 42, has been practicing in his chosen field for 10 years. He said the medical liability problem is so bad that he might be forced to consider relocating or working in an area that does not involve direct patient care. 
<br />
If he decides to leave Pennsylvania, he will be part of a troubling trend. 
<br />
Dr. Edward Dench Jr., president of the Pennsylvania Medical Society, announced in mid-July that an investigation of Federation of State Medical Boards reports revealed the state had a net loss of 1,072 physicians from 2001 to 2002. 
<br />
When the medical society reviewed data from the U.S. Health and Human Services' Bureau of Health Professions, it found that Pennsylvania experienced a 36 percent drop in general surgeons from 1997 to 2002. The state witnessed a 16 percent decline in orthopedic surgeons from 1997 to 2002 and a 16 percent reduction in neurosurgeons from 1995 to 2002. 
<br />
The information from the medical society does not directly link any of the figures to the medical malpractice crisis. However, Dr. Dench states that anecdotal stories collected by the Pennsylvania Medical Society demonstrate that physicians are leaving the state, retiring early or giving up high-risk procedures. 
<br />
Figures show that the total physician population per 1,000 citizens in Pittsburgh peaked in 2001 at 2.47. 
<br />
LaBuda said his practice paid $12,800 in malpractice premiums in 1998, and the number has soared to approximately $60,000 this year. 
<br />
He said relief can only be provided with a comprehensive reform plan that calls for a cap on the recovery of noneconomic damages in lawsuits. 
<br />
Pennsylvania Gov. Edward Rendell unveiled his medical malpractice liability reform plan in early June, vowing that his proposed solutions should keep physicians in the state. 
<br />
Rendell's plan calls for provider reimbursement, relief from high premiums, patient safety initiatives and tort and insurance reforms.
<br />
Due to the length of time it takes for lawsuits to progress through the legal system, it will take a few years before the proposals could conceivably translate into increased affordability and availability of malpractice insurance. 
<br />
Therefore, the governor's plan, which builds on a foundation of reform that was started by the General Assembly last year, aims to provide immediate relief by paying the Medical Care Availability and Reduction of Error premiums for the practicing surgeons, obstetricians, orthopedic surgeons and neurosurgeons who have the highest malpractice costs. 
<br />
Alan Rosenbloom, president of the Pennsylvania Health Care Association in Harrisburg, argues that long-term care providers also deserve MCARE premium relief, but have been overlooked in the governor's proposal. He said long-term care providers faced surcharge and assessment increases of 121 percent in 2002 and 42 percent this year. 
<br />
Dr. Paul Cervone, a member of the Washington County Medical Society and an obstetrician/gynecologist who practices at Valley Women's Health in Monongahela and Pleasant Hills, Pa., said Rendell's plan has some valid points, but falls short of providing all the right answers. 
<br />
The insurance premiums for his group have nearly doubled in recent years, while other local physicians have been unable to obtain obstetric insurance. 
<br />
"The governor's proposal fails to address caps on noneconomic damages. Historically, this has been the cornerstone of liability reform in other states. It also fails to define how it will be funded,'' said Cervone. 
<br />
The Pennsylvania Trial Lawyers Association in Harrisburg, Pa., maintains, however, that caps would punish the victims of avoidable medical mistakes and would not reduce premiums. 
<br />
Chuck Moran, director of media and public relations for the state's medical society, said two key tort reforms are needed to bring stability back into the liability insurance market. 
<br />
"First, attorney contingency fees need to be capped. The governor has proposed this. However, his proposal is quite generous toward trial lawyers, so it would need to be strengthened in order to be effective,'' said Moran. 
<br />
"Second, after a person has been fully compensated for economic loss, a reasonable limit should be placed on noneconomic awards," he said. 
<br />
Tracy Carbasho is a writer for the Pittsburgh Business Times, an affiliated newspaper.
<br />
