<br />
I think it's very important to take into consideration that lobbyists and witnesses changed thier stories when put under oath. They denied saying things they had said prior, even when confronted with thier previous statements in writing.
<br />

<br />
I also think it's very important to take into consideration the Wiess ratings study that showed placing a cap on awards has done nothing to lower malpractice insurance premiums.
<br />

<br />
Propr 108 is also something of note that will show California, even after having a cap of $250,000 ut in place in 1975, still had a rise in premiums in the mid '80s until prop 108 was put into effect. It was not award caps that worked for California, it was insurance regulation. This cap has also not been adjusted in the last 30 years to allow for inflation, or cost of living rises. Nice.
<br />

<br />
I guess everything costs the same now as it did 30 years ago. If you agree that placing a hard cap on awards is fair, then you must agree that placing a hard cap on premiums is fair. It's the same thing.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
