</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I think it's very important to take into consideration that lobbyists and witnesses changed thier stories when put under oath. They denied saying things they had said prior, even when confronted with thier previous statements in writing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It’s not a bad idea to put people under oath when testifying about issues of gravity to government bodies. If they denied, under oath, saying things that there was a record of them saying, why weren’t they slapped for perjury though? Would seem pretty cut-and-dry? If you don’t inflict the penalty now and then the deterrent is non-existent. We did, after all, impeach a president recently for suspected perjury.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I also think it's very important to take into consideration the Wiess ratings study that showed placing a cap on awards has done nothing to lower malpractice insurance premiums. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The Weiss study is a good source. The conclusions are good ones but there is still a message in there that I don’t think you’re receiving.
<br />

<br />
Notice, for example. that the premium increase was 35.9-48.2% during a period where the claims increase was 83.3-127.9%.
<br />

<br />
The study is also using a median claim number instead of an average and some of the other information posted here argues that the increase in the value of rewards at the high end may be more significant that the increase in the rest of the spectrum. If the top 10% of rewards doubled, the median would not change.
<br />

<br />
The six other factors having a greater impact on rates than the absence of caps are a good list also.
<br />

<br />
1. Medical inflation is, without drastic and unpopular action, not going to be reduced in the near future.
<br />

<br />
2. The insurance business cycle has aggravated the situation. The industry was able to undercharge during the 90’s due to high investment returns. High investment returns are gone, can’t undercharge anymore.
<br />

<br />
3. If reserves need to be shored up, the money is going to have to come from somewhere.
<br />

<br />
4. The decline in investment income isn’t going to get better soon. Insurers invest more in fixed income securities than in equities. The market value of these securities is going to drop when interest rates start to increase. Conversely, overall investment income will continue to suffer as the insurers have to buy more and more bonds at these low rates. This isn’t really a fixable issue.
<br />

<br />
5. Financial security of the insurers is going to become an increasing issue. As states engage in reform and try to cap, or slow the growth of, rates going forward insurers are going to get into increasing trouble and the incentive to exit the industry entirely will grow.
<br />

<br />
6. Supply and demand issues continue to be aggravated by the incentive for insurers to exit the industry as other lines of insurance are more profitable.
<br />

<br />
Weiss’s recommendations are interesting also, I don’t agree with them entirely.
<br />

<br />
The first one is the most troubling to me. While it was shown that there wasn’t a direct and immediate connection to lower premiums for tort reform, it was shown that the reform slowed claims which would allow the insurers to address some of the other issues that Weiss brought up, such as increasing reserves. If the situation truly is as dire as Weiss is describing, reducing the outflow of dollars from insurers should be a priority.
<br />

<br />
The second one, I agree with in principle and it would be easy enough to implement. Tougher reserving regulations for this line of business could easily be passed preventing insurers from keeping rates artificially low during good times. The problem would be: Where to get the money to bring existing reserves up to regulation? An increase in the burden of the reserve formula would create a large immediate need for cash. If the goal is to decrease premiums, what other options are there for raising this capital? Would this also not increase the incentive for insurers to exit the industry and thus aggravate the supply/demand issue?
<br />

<br />
The third one, I agree with wholeheartedly. If, within any given specialty, a small number of physicians really are responsible for a large proportion of the damages, why isn’t the medical care industry doing something about this for their own good?
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Propr 108 is also something of note that will show California, even after having a cap of $250,000 ut in place in 1975, still had a rise in premiums in the mid '80s until prop 108 was put into effect. It was not award caps that worked for California, it was insurance regulation. This cap has also not been adjusted in the last 30 years to allow for inflation, or cost of living rises. Nice. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
They both worked. There is nothing to say that one would have worked without the other in California, which is a pretty unique state. Also, the situation in the 80’s, while similar in some ways, is not the same as it is now.
<br />

<br />
I wouldn’t argue for any cap that isn’t indexed to inflation. Don’t assign that argument to be by default.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I guess everything costs the same now as it did 30 years ago. If you agree that placing a hard cap on awards is fair, then you must agree that placing a hard cap on premiums is fair. It's the same thing. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Again, I never argued that a cap shouldn’t be indexed or that the cost of things hasn’t changed over the past 30 years.
<br />

<br />
Sure, legislate a cap on premiums. You can’t legislate that insurance companies have to lose money so you’ll simply end up with nobody offering malpractice insurance, which is even worse for the victims of serious malpractice as the doctors won’t be able to afford to pony-up.
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
You see Shady, I’m not proclaiming that these caps in particular, or tort reform in general, is the holy grail to solve this problem. I’m arguing that it’s an important start. Further regulation of the insurance industry, as far as increasing reserves, etc. wouldn’t be a bad thing either. Regulating premiums directly, however, is always going to be a recipe for disaster in the long run.
<br />

<br />
Even people who believe that insurance companies are inherently evil must recognize that these companies are just an entitled to make a profit as any other company should be. If they are making reasonable and consistent profits, that’s a sign of health in the industry not one of disease. If the regulatory environment is changed such that the line is no longer profitable, there won’t be any more insurance. Then the government will have to step in with other heavy handed solutions, which are never efficient when coming from government.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
