<br />
A few points I would like to address, as I don't have too terribly much to disagree with you on.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I’m glad you had the time. I’ve taken the time to read yours also as a matter of courtesy. The statistic you quoted sarcastically as an epidemic is a number from 1990 and doesn’t tie into the financial cost so it’s not germane to the topic in contention. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Actually the numbers I quoted I have seen in many places for many years. 
<br />

<br />
Medical malpractice is not something that is filled frivolously. Addidtionally, the really high dollar pay outs are for gross negligence from doctors resulting in permanant damages, or death. One doesn't recieve a high dollar pay out simply for making an accusation, and the burden of proof lies with the acusor. Juries are also very sympathetic to doctors, and are not likely to award something without some pretty compelling evidence that the patient would not have been permanantly disabled or would not have died otherwise.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">It’s not a bad idea to put people under oath when testifying about issues of gravity to government bodies. If they denied, under oath, saying things that there was a record of them saying, why weren’t they slapped for perjury though? Would seem pretty cut-and-dry? If you don’t inflict the penalty now and then the deterrent is non-existent. We did, after all, impeach a president recently for suspected perjury. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Because it's not perjury if it's not said under oath. They told the truth under oath, hence no grounds for perjury.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">The third one, I agree with wholeheartedly. If, within any given specialty, a small number of physicians really are responsible for a large proportion of the damages, why isn’t the medical care industry doing something about this for their own good? </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
