<br />

<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Even people who believe that insurance companies are inherently evil must recognize that these companies are just an entitled to make a profit as any other company should be. If they are making reasonable and consistent profits, that’s a sign of health in the industry not one of disease. If the regulatory environment is changed such that the line is no longer profitable, there won’t be any more insurance. Then the government will have to step in with other heavy handed solutions, which are never efficient when coming from government.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I do agree that insurance companies are entitled to make a profit. It's when the degree of profit is much more important that quality customer care that I disagree with. I'm not suggesting to change so much that it is no longer profitable, but when some providers are pulling out and others are price gouging, something should be done to regulate that.
<br />

<br />
The government stepped in with heavy handed solutions when placing a hard cap on awards, which imo was not efficient. I don't believe there should be a hard cap on premiums, either. A little regulation in that area wouldn't hurt, however.
<br />

<br />

<br />
Just as an aside, attorneys are held to the same standards in client care as doctors are, and can also be sues for malpractice. Attorneys are not screaming about the cost of thier premiums. Do you know why? They are state regulated.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
