	<tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><span class="name"><a name="866647"></a><b>Sshadow</b></span><br /><span class="postdetails"><strong></strong>Ancient<br /><img src="images/ranks/rank6.gif" alt="Ancient" title="Ancient" border="0" /><br /><br /><br />Joined: 09 Jan 2002<br />Posts: 3160<br />Location: Utah</span><br /></td>
		<td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
				<td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=866647&amp;sid=3937a42551fdeda95901cb3c4f05667b#866647"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Mon Feb 02, 2004 2:40 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
				<td valign="top" align="right" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=866647&amp;sid=3937a42551fdeda95901cb3c4f05667b"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
			</tr>
			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I'm glad that we've had this discussion. I now better understand your point of view on the topic, and I believe you better understand mine. 
<br />

<br />
A few points I would like to address, as I don't have too terribly much to disagree with you on. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Yes, I agree that we’re coming closer to understanding the other’s position.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Actually the numbers I quoted I have seen in many places for many years. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
The particular numbers you quoted this time around were (emphasis yours):
<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Prevalence of Medical Malpractice: A study (generally known as the Harvard study) commissioned by New York State in 1986, and released in 1990, showed that actual malpractice is relatively rare. Of the New York hospital cases examined, the incidence of adverse events, or injuries resulting from medical "interventions" or treatment, was 3.7 percent. The percentage of adverse events due to what the physician team characterized as "negligence" (not necessarily a legal definition) was 1 percent. <span style="font-weight: bold"> However, only one in eight who suffered from an adverse event due to negligence filed a medical malpractice claim, and only one in 15 received compensation. </span></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />
That’s why I said it was a number from 1990.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Actually the numbers I quoted I have seen in many places for many years. 
<br />

<br />
Medical malpractice is not something that is filled frivolously. Addidtionally, the really high dollar pay outs are for gross negligence from doctors resulting in permanant damages, or death. One doesn't recieve a high dollar pay out simply for making an accusation, and the burden of proof lies with the acusor. Juries are also very sympathetic to doctors, and are not likely to award something without some pretty compelling evidence that the patient would not have been permanantly disabled or would not have died otherwise. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This is an issue on which we still do not agree. I do agree that the vast majority of malpractice cases are not filed frivolously by most measures. I do believe that the top end of the reward spectrum is extreme.
<br />

<br />
The real monetary value of a the human life is already compensated for before we get to the portion of damages we are speaking of capping, and the value is usually uncomfortably small for people to accept but the equations for coming up with it are well understood and logical. Likewise, the cost of pertinent medical care and assistance for the life of the person injured is already taken care of before we get to the portion of which we speak.
<br />

<br />
The portion, of which we speak, is a monetary figure attached to a non-monetary, nebulous, thing and is often tacked on for something that smells of vengeance, not justice.
<br />

<br />
For example, if an Obstetrician the doctor on a case where the fetus strangulated on it’s umbilical cord during delivery and died (or suffered brain damage), that’s a tragedy. If it can be shown that, had the Obstetrician been in the room during crucial period of time doing his job, the tragedy could very likely have been averted, that’s hard (impossible) to accept for a grieving couple. That the Obstetrician could have been overworked at the time with multiple deliveries, needed to go to the cafeteria to grab some food, or something else is not acceptable. The grieving parents must be compensated. Any medical and/or burial costs must be covered.
<br />

<br />
Are they, however, entitled to $1mil in compensation? Hell no. It’s offensive to me that people think that they should be. You shouldn’t be able to get rich because you suffered a tragedy. If you didn’t have any reasonable expectation of ever having $1mil free and clear at this stage of your life had your child lived, what right do you have profiting from such misfortune. It sickens me.
<br />

<br />
Compensating pain and suffering is a tricky thing. Everyone’s life contains it. Nobody has the right to expect a life free of it. I don’t think that anything other than say six months worth of living expenses should be covered over and above counseling, medical, and burial expenses for the loss of a child. Both parents should be able to take FMLA unpaid time off and be compensated for that. They should be able to get counseling, and be compensated for that. They should experience no out-of-pocket expense relating to the tragedy. Anything more than a year’s worth of living expenses is obscene to me.
<br />

<br />
This may, in fact, be the issue on which we disagree most.
<br />

<br />
What financial burden does the death of a child cause someone? It’s an indescribable emotional tragedy that cannot be compensated for. So why does throwing money at it make it any better? People should be able to take time off and seek counseling to try to cope with such a devastating loss. People should not, however, be rewarded for it. Ever. They should not be financially better off for the death of their child. That’s wrong.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Because it's not perjury if it's not said under oath. They told the truth under oath, hence no grounds for perjury. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Sure it is. If they deny, under oath, ever making a specific statement and it can be proven that that statement was made that is perjury. It doesn’t matter whether the statement in question was made under oath, it’s the denial that’s the perjury.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> This is my exact question. Doctors with multiple infractions are still practicing medicine. I don't know why doctors are not more self-governing than they are, but perhaps they think admitting that a peer has been careless makes them look like they could be careless also. I don't know though. 
<br />

<br />
This is a statistic I have seen may times; that very few doctors make up the majority of med-mal claims. I am in complete agreement with you when wondering why something more isn't being done about it. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
I suspect that the statistic that most complaints come from a few flawed doctors is, in itself, flawed. The subject warrants further study, however. If it can be shown to be true, the medical profession needs to answer for it and address it.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> My appologies. I was wrong for making that assumption. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Accepted, thank you.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> I do agree that insurance companies are entitled to make a profit. It's when the degree of profit is much more important that quality customer care that I disagree with. I'm not suggesting to change so much that it is no longer profitable, but when some providers are pulling out and others are price gouging, something should be done to regulate that. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
There are always some companies where money is more important than service in any industry. Competition is what keeps this from becoming chronic.
<br />

<br />
The price gouging of which you speak is not necessarily that. Only predictable risks can be profitably insured. The turmoil in the marketplace caused by the retreat of several significant providers causes the level of predictability of the marketplace to decrease. Until it is stabilized, the risk is higher and therefore the premium is more. For this reason, more effort needs to be expended in stabilizing the marketplace and in encouraging more players to stay in the game.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> The government stepped in with heavy handed solutions when placing a hard cap on awards, which imo was not efficient. I don't believe there should be a hard cap on premiums, either. A little regulation in that area wouldn't hurt, however. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
We’re only talking of caps on one aspect of the reward equation, not anywhere near the entire thing. Comparing that to capping the entire premium is not a fair comparison.
<br />

<br />
A little intelligent regulation would certainly not be terribly harmful. The Weiss study shows that the industry is still largely undercapitalized, however, so regulation will likely result in higher premiums in the short term in order to make the system more healthy in the long term. This is all well and good except that doctors are pleading for short-term relief because expenses are already too high.
<br />

<br />
The situation almost begs for a government bailout, as distasteful as that is to me, unless a few years of increased pain can be endured by the doctors in order to stabilize things.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote"> Just as an aside, attorneys are held to the same standards in client care as doctors are, and can also be sues for malpractice. Attorneys are not screaming about the cost of thier premiums. Do you know why? They are state regulated. </td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Insurance agents, CPA’s, and other professionals have the same issues. I must carry Errors &amp; Omissions insurance myself, in fact. The risks are always much higher for doctors though, and so the rewards are also much higher. If a lawyer screws up for just a moment, people generally don’t lose their health and/or die. It’s really a different discussion for other, non-medical, professionals than it is for doctors.</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
		</table></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
